Reviews/
Networking/
Wireless Networking/






















John R. Delaney




Luma Home WiFi System
The Luma Home WiFi System is designed to extend your wireless network to all parts of your home. It's very easy to install, but it's pricey, and performance is mixed.





Luma Home WiFi System








By 

John R. Delaney



June 23, 2016 4:08PM EST
June 23, 2016



Editors' Rating: 

good













View Gallery

View All 6 Photos in Gallery




MSRP 
$399.00













Pros
Easy to install and configure. Built-in security and content filtering. Good close-proximity throughput in testing.


Cons
Expensive. Limited Ethernet ports. Lacks dedicated band control. No advanced management settings. Middling range performance.


Bottom Line
The Luma Home WiFi System is designed to extend your wireless network to all parts of your home. It's very easy to install, but it's pricey, and performance is mixed.







There's a new type of wireless product hitting the market: Wi-Fi systems use individual modules to create a mesh network that delivers wireless networking to all areas of your home. The Luma Home WiFi System ($399; 3-pack, or $149 each) joins the Eero, AmpliFi, and Plume systems as the latest modular Wi-Fi solution to tout ease of use and whole-house coverage. Luma makes it easy to invite users to a guest network and to create filter policies for each user. The system delivered good close-proximity throughput in our testing, but we found that performance took a hit as we moved away from the main module. Moreover, management options and ports are limited. For half the price, you can pick up a traditional midrange router, like our Editors' Choice Linksys EA7500 Max-Stream AC1900 MU-MIMO Gigabit Router, which delivers much better overall throughput and offers plenty of ports and management settings.

//Compare Similar Products
Compare





Linksys EA7500 Max-Stream AC1900 MU-MIMO Gigabit Router






 




 







Eero






 



 







Asus Google OnHub SRT-AC1900






 



 







Starry Station






 



 







Netgear Nighthawk X6 AC3200 Tri-Band WiFi Router






 



 







Linksys AC3200 Tri-Band Gigabit Smart Wi-Fi Router (EA9200)






 



 







D-Link AC3200 Ultra Wi-Fi Router (DIR-890L/R)






 




 







Asus RT-AC3200 Tri-Band Router






 



 







Netgear Nighthawk X4S Smart Wi-Fi Router (R7800)






 



 







Asus RT-AC88U Dual-Band Router






 




 







Synology Router RT1900ac






 



 







TP-Link AC1900 Touch Screen Wi-Fi Gigabit Router Touch P5






 



 







Tenda F3 N300 Wireless Router






 




 












Design and Features
The 3-pack system of routers reviewed here (which Luma refers to as modules) is designed for the typical home, but you can add more modules (up to ten on a single network) if you require more coverage. In the box, you also get three power supplies, and one Ethernet cable. The hexagon-shaped modules are available in white, gold, orange, or silver, and measure 4.1 by 4.6 by 1.1 inches (HWD). There's a round LED ring on the face of the module that flashes blue during the initial setup, green when configuring the Wi-Fi network, and red when there's an error. The light goes out when everything is up and running. The modules communicate with one another via a proprietary mesh network and are designed to be placed within 40 feet of each other to blanket your home with Wi-Fi coverage.

View All 6 Photos in Gallery


Each module is an 802.11ac router and contains a quad-core processor and two radio bands (2.4GHz and 5GHz). They are AC1200 routers with a maximum data rate of 300Mbps on the 2.4GHz band and 867Mbps on the 5GHz band, as well as support for Multi-User Multiple Input, Multiple Output (MU-MIMO) data streaming. As with the Asus Google OnHub SRT-AC1900 router, the Luma uses automatic band steering and chooses which band is best, based on location and load. It's a nice feature, but it shows up as a single SSID, which means you can't dedicate a band to specific devices, such as gaming consoles and media servers. You only get one Gigabit LAN port on each module; it's on the back of the device and is joined by a Gigabit WAN input and a USB 2.0 port. The USB port can be used for charging peripherals, but at the time of this writing, it was not yet able to connect to USB hard drives.
The Luma network is controlled using a mobile app for Android and iOS users. As with the Starry Station, the Eero, and the Asus Google OnHub routers, the Luma does not offer a Web-based management console and can only be accessed and controlled using a mobile device. The app opens to the Wi-Fi page, which shows the placement of each module in a generic home floor plan. It tells you how many Luma devices are online, as well as your current upload and download speeds. Swiping the screen to the left brings you to a page where you can see each module by name; tapping a module displays the status and IP address for that module. The three-bar icon on the upper-left corner takes you to the Main Menu, where you can access Wi-Fi and Account settings, launch an online help page, and shop for Luma devices on Amazon.

Wi-Fi settings are limited to changing the network's name and password and enabling the Guest Network, and Account settings are limited to changing the name of each module. There are no QoS, Firewall, or Port Forwarding settings, nor are there settings for creating access schedules. Parental controls include a Content Filter policy with five rating levels: Unrestricted, R-rated, PG-13, PG, and G. You can apply a rating across the entire network or add users, and assign a different level to each user as you see fit. When you add a user, you can also add their frequently used client devices to make sure the filters are always in place. You can use the Control page to give users access to your guest network via text or email and to add new Luma modules to the network. There's also a Pause button that instantly switches off Internet access across the network until you disable it.
The Luma offers a built-in Security feature that continually scans all connected devices for malware and vulnerabilities to hacking and viruses. It will quarantine infected devices and attempt to purge them of infections, and will send a push alert to your mobile device when something is detected. You can check your status by tapping the Security icon on the bottom of the Home screen.
Installation and Performance
To install the Luma routers, you have to download the free Android or iOS app. When you first open the app, you press the Setup Luma button and select how many modules you are installing. You'll be asked to answer questions, such as what type of home you live in (single-family, apartment/condo, or townhouse) and how many floors are in your home. I chose single-family home with two floors (basement and main floor).

You then have to tell the app where your router/modem is located by clicking on an area of your home (front, back, middle, upstairs, or downstairs) and then create a network name and password. The app will prompt you to plug in the first Luma module, connect it to your modem, and restart the modem. You can then name the module using a list of room names (Master Bedroom, Kitchen, Office, etc). The light ring will spin blue briefly and turn solid blue when the module is initialized. Press the Start Wi-Fi button and wait for the light ring to flash green seven times. It will turn off when it's ready. The entire process took less than five minutes for me. You can tap Add Another Luma to install additional Luma modules or you can opt to add more at a later time.
When adding more Luma modules, the process is similar to that of setting up the first module, but the app will tell you where to install your next module based on the location of the first device. In my case, it was the upstairs center of my house. It took around one minute to initialize, and 25 seconds for the Wi-Fi setup. The app had me install the third module in the center of my basement, and the installation was as quick as the first two.
 See How We Test Wireless Routers
Performance in testing was mixed. I ran my usual throughput tests, but since I could not isolate the radio bands, results are based on the Luma's band-steering feature. On the close-proximity (same-room) test for the main module (the one connected to my modem), the Luma delivered an impressive 457Mbps. That's right up there with the Linksys EA7500 (495Mbps) and much faster than the Eero (188.7Mbps) and the Asus Google OnHub (307Mbps). The Starry Station managed 398Mbps on this test. On the 30-foot test the Luma's score of 76.1Mbps edged past the Eero (71.2Mbps) and beat the Asus Google OnHub (39.8Mbps) handily, but couldn't keep pace with the Starry Station (160Mbps) and the Linksys EA7500 (298Mbps).
I ran the same tests on each of the two satellite modules and found that the close-proximity throughput was significantly reduced (106Mbps for the upstairs module, and 101Mbps for the basement module), while the 30-foot test scores were nearly identical to the main module (77.2Mbps and 75Mbps, respectively).
Conclusion
The Luma Home WiFi System is a good bet if you seek simplicity when setting up and maintaining a home Wi-Fi network. Like Eero, it's relatively expensive, especially if you need more than three modules to cover your home, but technically challenged users will appreciate its built-in parental controls and no-hassle security features. If you want total control over your network, however, the Luma will likely disappoint, in which case you're better off with a traditional device, such as the Linksys EA7500 Max-Stream AC1900 MU-MIMO Gigabit Router, our Editors' Choice for midrange routers. It's about half the price of the Luma system, offers better throughput performance, and is packed with features, including multiple LAN ports and plentiful management settings.


PCMag may earn affiliate commissions from the shopping links included on this page. These commissions do not affect how we test, rate or review products. To find out more, read our complete terms of use.


















 



